<subSubSection lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="328" pageId="20" pageNumber="326" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1436,1977,2040]" lastBlockId="22.[151,1437,150,1078]" lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="328" pageId="20" pageNumber="326">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,1977,2003]" pageId="20" pageNumber="326">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. In the key of 
<bibRefCitation author="Lundbeck, W." box="[427,620,1977,2003]" pageId="20" pageNumber="326" refId="ref14900" refString="Lundbeck, W. (1922) Diptera Danica Part VI Pipunculidae, Phoridae. Wesley, London, 447 pp." type="book" year="1922">Lundbeck (1922)</bibRefCitation>
for Group IV it runs to couplet 
<specimenCount box="[973,1038,1977,2003]" pageId="20" pageNumber="326" type="generic">
33 
<taxonomicName authority="(Wood)" baseAuthorityName="Wood" baseAuthorityYear="1909" box="[1007,1038,1978,2003]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="326" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barbulata">
<emphasis box="[1007,1038,1978,2003]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="326">M.</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</specimenCount>
barbulata (Wood), but it has a very different hypopygium (
<figureCitation box="[411,477,2013,2039]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–11" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[271,1312,181,1913]" captionTargetId="figure-31@1.[268,1320,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–11. Megaselia culmenensis n. sp. male. 1, frons; 2, antennae, palps and proboscis; 3, postpedicel; 4, side of thorax; 5, dorsal view of abdominal tergites 2–6; 6; left face of hypopygioum; 7–8, right faces of hypopygium; 9, front tarsus; 10, hind femur; 11, wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4925221" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4925221/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="326">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[463,477,2013,2039]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.08" pageId="20" pageNumber="326" unit="in" value="2.0">2</quantity>
</figureCitation>
in 
<bibRefCitation author="Disney, R. H. L." box="[513,665,2013,2039]" pageId="20" pageNumber="326" pagination="93 - 94" refId="ref14059" refString="Disney, R. H. L. (1991) Two rare scuttle flies (Diptera, Phoridae) from Yorkshire, including one new for Britain. Naturalist, Hull, 116, 93 - 94." type="journal article" year="1991">Disney, 1991</bibRefCitation>
). In the key to the males of the British species (
<bibRefCitation author="Disney R. H. L." box="[1195,1346,2013,2039]" pageId="20" pageNumber="326" pagination="1 - 155" refId="ref14009" refString="Disney R. H. L. (1989) Scuttle Flies-Diptera Phoridae Genus Megaselia. Handbooks for the Identification of British Insects 10 (8), Royal Entomologicai Society of London, 1 - 155. https: // doi. org / 10.1163 / 187631287 X 00115" type="book chapter" year="1989">Disney, 1989</bibRefCitation>
) it runs to couplet 102, but its hypopygium differs from both species. In the keys of 
<bibRefCitation author="Schmitz H. &amp; Beyer" box="[1003,1279,150,177]" pageId="22" pageNumber="328" pagination="513 - 608" refId="ref15062" refString="Schmitz H. &amp; Beyer (1965) Phoridae. In: Lindner, E. (Ed.), Die Fliegen der palaearktischen Region 4 (33) (Lieferung 258, 260). E. Schweizerbart'sche Verlagsbuchhandlung, Stuttgart, pp. 513 - 608." type="book chapter" year="1965">Schmitz &amp; Beyer (1965)</bibRefCitation>
for Abteilung IV Zweite Reihe it runs couplet 71. However, the supposed difference in the number of costal cilia between the two options is negated by reference to their photo of the wing for 
<taxonomicName authority="Schmitz. The" authorityName="Schmitz. The" authorityYear="1934" box="[930,1212,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="raetica">
<emphasis box="[930,1049,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="328">M. raetica</emphasis>
Schmitz. The
</taxonomicName>
latter has a clearly different hypopygium from the two species encountered by proceeding to couplet 72. Our species has a hypopygium similar but different from those of 
<taxonomicName authority="Schmitz" authorityName="Schmitz" authorityYear="1935" box="[540,790,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fusciclava">
<emphasis box="[540,692,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="328">M. fusciclava</emphasis>
Schmitz
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Lundbeck)" baseAuthorityName="Lundbeck" baseAuthorityYear="1920" box="[845,1145,295,322]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuscipalpis">
<emphasis box="[845,1003,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="328">M. fuscipalpis</emphasis>
(Lundbeck)
</taxonomicName>
. The latter is immediately distinguished by its legs being entirely dark brown. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schmitz" authorityYear="1935" box="[728,879,331,357]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fusciclava">
<emphasis box="[728,879,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="328">M. fusciclava</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from our species in having a posterodorsal hair palisade on all 5 segments of the front tarsus and its costal index exceeding 0.48. In Bormeier’s (1964) key for Nearctic Group IV species it runs to couplet 17 lead 
<specimenCount box="[758,811,403,429]" pageId="22" pageNumber="328" type="generic">
1 
<taxonomicName authority="(Malloch)" baseAuthorityName="Malloch" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[780,811,403,428]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="difficilis">
<emphasis box="[780,811,403,428]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="328">M.</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</specimenCount>
difficilis (Malloch), but its wing has 6 axillary bristles and clearly longer costal cilia at 
<quantity box="[525,692,439,465]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6999999999999997" metricValueMax="1.7999999999999998" metricValueMin="1.6" pageId="22" pageNumber="328" unit="mm" value="0.16999999999999998" valueMax="0.18" valueMin="0.16">0.16–0.18 mm</quantity>
. It fails to run down in keys for the rest of the world’s fauna and subsequent additions.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4925249" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4925249" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4925249/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="327" startId="21.[151,264,1943,1967]" targetBox="[157,1433,187,1908]" targetPageId="21">
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,1943,2040]" pageId="21" pageNumber="327">
